pulfalight.title: Non Princeton Aeon Users lose their Shopping Cart

comments.body:
Atlas tech support recommends we do the following. Update our code to only submit the following params a single time in a given post:

AeonForm
DocumentType
GroupingIdentifier
GroupingOption_CallNumber
GroupingOption_ItemDate
GroupingOption_ItemInfo1
GroupingOption_ItemInfo3
GroupingOption_ItemInfo4
GroupingOption_ItemNumber
GroupingOption_ItemTitle
GroupingOption_ItemVolume
GroupingOption_Location
GroupingOption_ReferenceNumber
GroupingOption_Site
Location
RequestType
SubmitButton
SystemID
UserReview
WebRequestForm

Currently we submit these params for every container included in a given POST request. Additionally they recommend the values for these two params should be set to the following values:
AeonForm=EADRequest
WebRequestForm=EADRequest

AeonForm tells Aeon that the POST contains EAD data, WebRequestForm tells Aeon which aeon request form the requests submitted should be edited in within the Aeon web interface if the end user decides to do that.

rdss-handbook.title: Proposal to remove the "Done" Zenhub column
Proposal to remove the "Post MVP" Zenhub column

comments.body:
I really appreciate the thought you're putting into our development process, thank you! I agree that we should remove the "done" column -- it seems redundant to me. 
However, I think it is useful to have a place to put tickets to make it clear that we are not planning to work on them in the near term. Even though we do not look at those tickets during sprint planning, we're always going to get many more feature requests than we can actually address. Giving someone an outlet to write a ticket and putting that ticket somewhere (even if it's in a place like an "icebox" column) seems useful to me. Where would these tickets go otherwise? I would not want to put them into "product backlog" because they are not necessarily things that we as a team want to commit to ever doing.
We have been utilizing the tickets in this column for work for the students.
